   </xocs:meta><xocs:serial-item xmlns:xoe="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/xoe/dtd">
      <article xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/ja/dtd" docsubtype="fla" xml:lang="en" version="5.6">
         <item-info>
            <jid>GECCO</jid>
            <aid>2245</aid>
            <ce:article-number>e02245</ce:article-number>
            <ce:pii>S2351-9894(22)00247-5</ce:pii>
            <ce:doi>10.1016/j.gecco.2022.e02245</ce:doi>
            <ce:copyright type="other" year="2022">The Authors</ce:copyright>
         </item-info>
         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="fig0005">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0005">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0005" view="all">(a) Location of Pasoh Forest Reserve, Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia, and (b) map of the 49 calling points detected in December 2018, February and March 2019, and July and August 2019 by using acoustic triangulation from the two towers (marked with ×). Multiple calling points may have been used by the same individual or group, such that the distance between the calling points does not necessarily reflect the distance between different individuals or groups. The numbers along the two axes are distance (m) expressed as Malayan Rectified Skew Orthomorphic (Peninsular Malaysia), with Kertau 48 as Datum.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0005" role="short">Fig. 1</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0005" locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S2351989422002475/gr1"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0010">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0010" view="all">Schematic illustration of sampling forest vertical components (FVCs: DTM, digital terrain model; DSM, digital surface model; CH, canopy height) within a calling location, which is delineated with the calling point at the center of the circle and four different radius sizes (20, 50, 100, and 150 m). FVC data were collected by LiDAR census and mapped in every 2.5-m × 2.5-m grid interval. Each calling point was detected by the bearing angle measured from the two towers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0005" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). Circles of four sizes were drawn to cover all FVCs at longer distances from the tower; for example, for a triangle with a 5° ( ± 2.5° on both sides of the bearing angle) vertex at the tower and a circle of 100-m radius, a distance of &lt; 1200 m covers all the FVC data.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0010" role="short">Fig. 2</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0010" locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S2351989422002475/gr2"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0015">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">Comparison of the frequency distribution (%) of forest vertical components (FVCs) between calling locations and the whole study site: (a) digital terrain model (DTM), (b) digital surface model (DSM), and (c) canopy height (CH). The bars of each FVC represent the average value of five trials (sets) of 3000 randomly collected samples from calling locations of 20-m radius and the whole study site (see <ce:cross-ref id="cr0010" refid="sec0070">Appendix 4</ce:cross-ref> for calling locations of 50- and 150-m radius and the results of statistical analysis for the comparison of the whole study site and calling locations). Note that “calling points” are voice orientation points triangulated from the two canopy towers (see <ce:cross-ref id="cr0015" refid="sec0025">Section 3.2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0020" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b), whereas “calling locations” are estimated circular calling areas of different size radius (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0025" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0015" role="short">Fig. 3</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0015" locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S2351989422002475/gr3"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0020">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Frequency distribution of convexity index (CI) based on the digital terrain model obtained in all 20-m × 20-m sub-blocks where the calling points were located and across the whole study site. Note that the sub-block of a calling point was determined by the exact calling point, not by the larger calling locations (as shown in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0030" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0020" role="short">Fig. 4</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0020" locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S2351989422002475/gr4"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0025">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0025" view="all">Spatial distribution of PCA scores of PC-1 (above) and PC-2 (below). All scores were analyzed on the basis of the standard deviation (SD) of each forest vertical component (FVCs: DTM, digital terrain model; DSM, digital surface model; CH, canopy height) and the convexity index (CI) and mapped in every 20-m × 20-m cell (mesh) of the study site, showing the potential distribution of calling locations. Higher scores can be regarded as locations with potentially greater probability for white-handed gibbons’ calling based on PC-1 and PC-2. The end lines of the four sides (east, west, south, and north) were excluded from the analysis to avoid side effects and because CI could not be calculated. The boundaries between the land-use types (primary forest, regenerating forest, and oil palm plantation) are shown by white solid lines (corresponding to the boundaries shown in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0035" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b). The contour lines are placed at every 1 grade of scores in the upper map and every 1.5 grade in the lower map. The PC loading of each FVC is shown in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0040" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0025" role="short">Fig. 5</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0025" locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S2351989422002475/gr5"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" id="tbl0005" colsep="0" rowsep="0" frame="topbot">
               <ce:label>Table 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">Importance (proportion of variance) of each component (PC-1∼PC-4) in the PCA based on the forest vertical components.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0030" role="short">Table 1</ce:alt-text>
               <tgroup cols="5">
                  <colspec colnum="1" colname="col1"/>
                  <colspec colnum="2" colname="col2"/>
                  <colspec colnum="3" colname="col3"/>
                  <colspec colnum="4" colname="col4"/>
                  <colspec colnum="5" colname="col5"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd"/>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-1</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-2</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-3</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-4</entry>
                     </row>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Standard deviation</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">3.20</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">1.92</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">1.17</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.52</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Proportion of variance</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.66</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.24</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.09</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.02</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Cumulative proportion</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.66</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.90</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">0.98</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" align="char" char=".">1.00</entry>
                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
            </ce:table>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" id="tbl0010" colsep="0" rowsep="0" frame="topbot">
               <ce:label>Table 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0035" view="all">Component loadings of principal components 1, 2, 3, and 4 (PC-1∼PC-4) for each forest vertical component (FVC; DTM, digital terrain model; DSM, digital surface model; CH, canopy height) and convexity index (CI). Larger value indicates larger loading (correlation) on the component.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0035" role="short">Table 2</ce:alt-text>
               <tgroup cols="5">
                  <colspec colnum="1" colname="col1"/>
                  <colspec colnum="2" colname="col2"/>
                  <colspec colnum="3" colname="col3"/>
                  <colspec colnum="4" colname="col4"/>
                  <colspec colnum="5" colname="col5"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd"/>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-1</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-2</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">PC-3</entry>
