            <ce:date-received day="16" month="11" year="2021"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="26" month="7" year="2022"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="26" month="7" year="2022"/>
            <ce:abstract id="ab0010" class="author" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="abs0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0050" view="all">The aim of this study was to develop a tool that allows for rapid assessment of arboreal animal distributions. In our acoustic triangulation method, we placed directional microphones atop two canopy towers to get the bearings of calls, allowing us to study the spatial distribution of calling locations of white-handed gibbon (<ce:italic>Hylobates lar</ce:italic>) within 2400 ha of the Pasoh Forest Reserve in Peninsular Malaysia in relation to three forest vertical components. The calling locations were analyzed in relation to a digital surface model, a digital terrain model, and canopy height (difference between the first two parameters) derived from LiDAR data. The locations where 49 calling points originated were mapped during the survey period (December 2018 to August 2019). All forest vertical components at the calling locations were significantly higher than the average values over the whole study site, which suggests that white-handed gibbons choose taller canopy trees at locations with higher elevation. Topographically convex areas (ridgetops or upper hillslopes) tended to be chosen as calling locations over concave areas (e.g., valleys, lower slopes). In addition, calling locations were concentrated in primary forest rather than in regenerating forest, where the canopy height was shorter and more structurally homogeneous than in the primary forest. Based on these results, we mapped the area of high probability for gibbon calling locations by compiling the four parameters of forest vertical components using principal component analysis. This map based on the vertical aspects of vegetation can be helpful in properly managing the forest for gibbon conservation, enabling a rapid assessment of land-use plans within a geographic area where the calling locations occur with high probability.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            <ce:keywords id="keys0005" class="keyword" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0010">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="key0005">
                  <ce:text>Acoustic triangulation positioning</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0010">
                  <ce:text>Canopy tower</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0015">
                  <ce:text>Digital surface model</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0020">
                  <ce:text>Digital terrain model</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0025">
                  <ce:text>
                     <ce:italic>Hylobates lar</ce:italic>
                  </ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0030">
                  <ce:text>LiDAR</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0015">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0005" view="all">The data that has been used is confidential.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec0005" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0020">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0010" view="all">The rapid rates of deforestation and forest degradation in the tropics are causing biodiversity losses (e.g. <ce:cross-ref id="cr0100" refid="bib13">Convention on Biological Diversity, 2006</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0105" refid="bib62">Ritchie and Roser, 2017</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0110" refid="bib38">Leahy, 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, the development of rapid assessment tools is an urgent issue for the conservation of arboreal animals (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0115" refid="bib37">Larsen, 2016</ce:cross-ref>), particularly for umbrella species whose habitat and activities may be influenced by forest logging and land-use changes (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0005" refid="bib69 bib23 bib44">Terborgh, 1986; Geissmann, 2002; Marsh, 2003</ce:cross-refs>). In this respect, a tool that can evaluate forest canopy information is urgently needed for predicting the habitat conditions of arboreal animals.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0015" view="all">The white-handed gibbon (<ce:italic>Hylobates lar</ce:italic>) is an arboreal primate that is common in the Southeast Asian tropics (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0010" refid="bib22 bib27">Geissmann, 1991; Gron, 2010</ce:cross-refs>) and shows large variation in home range size (17–61 ha) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0120" refid="bib39">Light et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The species has been threatened by recent deforestation and forest degradation due to excessive timber extraction and land-use changes (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0015" refid="bib79 bib17">Whitmore, 1984; Fan, 2017</ce:cross-refs>), which resulted in smaller habitable spaces for the white-handed gibbons, as similarly reported in other arboreal primates (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0020" refid="bib7 bib52 bib5 bib12 bib48">Brockelman and Srikosamatara, 1993; Oka et al., 2000; Bartlett, 2007; Cheyne, 2007; Miettinen et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0020" view="all">Like the approximately 20 other gibbon species, the white-handed gibbon plays an important role as a keystone and umbrella species (largely frugivorous) that spreads food resources (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0025" refid="bib47 bib65 bib59">McConkey, 2000; Savini et al., 2008; Phiphatsuwannacha et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>), and forest management needs to be carefully planned to maintain the canopy height and structures suitable for these arboreal animals. For example, white-handed gibbons prefer tall trees for their sleeping sites (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0030" refid="bib1 bib61">Anderson, 1998; Reichard, 1998</ce:cross-refs>) and calling locations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0125" refid="bib79">Whitmore, 1984</ce:cross-ref>), as do other primates in general (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0130" refid="bib40">Maciej et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). However, such vertical height is not a necessary condition for their habitat, as <ce:cross-ref id="cr0135" refid="bib60">Phoonjampa et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref> reported gibbons’ active habitation in regenerating forest. Nevertheless, selective logging with the loss of many trees may result in gibbons’ losing their calling sites, particularly when the canopy structure is homogeneous owing to the loss of big merchantable trees. Therefore, three-dimensional data including vertical forest structure may provide better information for the conservation of arboreal animals, particularly in a spatially restricted forest reserve.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0025" view="all">As other gibbon species, white-handed gibbons produce long, loud, and relatively stereotyped song bouts in the morning (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0140" refid="bib23">Geissmann, 2002</ce:cross-ref>), enabling studies of their activities and pair bonding (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0145" refid="bib8">Brockelman et al., 1998</ce:cross-ref>) and spatial mapping of their territories (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0150" refid="bib12">Cheyne, 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0155" refid="bib46">Marshall et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0160" refid="bib3">Asensio et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0165" refid="bib75">Vu and Tran, 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Moreover, their habitat selection was reported to be related to the logging history, elevation, and density of large tree species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0035" refid="bib33 bib34 bib45">Johns, 1986, 1988; Marshall, 2009</ce:cross-refs>), but it remains unclear how their calling activities are related to forest environmental parameters. In this study, we focused on gibbon calling and call transmission in relation to the three-dimensional aspects of forest structure (e.g., spatial variation of canopy height). Such information is important when analyzing the activities of arboreal primates, given that their vocalizations can maintain their territories over long distances, even though they are usually invisible to observers. (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0170" refid="bib75">Vu and Tran, 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Considering the results of these reports, we expect that white-handed gibbons prefer certain calling locations, such as vertically higher places where fewer obstacles physically intercept transmission of their calls, as reported in sound propagation studies of other primates (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0040" refid="bib9 bib63 bib40">Brown et al., 1995; Sabatini and Ruiz-Miranda, 2008; Maciej et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Furthermore, spatially mapping the vertical aspects of white-handed gibbons’ calling locations should substantially improve our understanding of their habitat selection. In addition, the use of a canopy surface and terrain model to capture canopy surface information would help to improve our understanding of the relationship between white-handed gibbons’ calling and the selection of calling sites in relation to the spatial variation in canopy heights, as sounds produced from higher positions tend to propagate further (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0175" refid="bib19">Fang and Ling, 2003</ce:cross-ref>). Nevertheless, monitoring and mapping of white-handed gibbons’ calling can be labor-intensive work, particularly when calls are tracked from the forest floor (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0180" refid="bib74">Vu and Dong, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, we need a rapid assessment tool (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0185" refid="bib35">Keeping, 2014</ce:cross-ref>) that can provide spatial mapping of endangered arboreal animals’ activities (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0045" refid="bib77 bib78">Vu et al., 2018a, 2018b</ce:cross-refs>) in reference to their vocal sound propagation.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Use of remote sensing, particularly three-dimensional mapping technology such as stereoscopy of aerial photographs or LiDAR (light detecting and range) census, provides high-resolution mapping and enables GIS forest canopy surface information to be gathered (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0190" refid="bib57">Okuda et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Overlaying the spatial information related to the calling locations and GIS enables researchers to identify optimal calling locations (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0195" refid="bib25">Grantham et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>) and may eventually serve as a tool for GAP analysis (Geographical Approach for Protection of Biodiversity; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0200" refid="bib67">Scott et al., 1993</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0205" refid="bib66">Scott and Schipper, 2006</ce:cross-ref>), which aims to extrapolate from identified or observed points to the optimal habitat area by using and overlaying the GIS. Such an analysis is effective in tropical forest ecosystems, where arboreal primates are relatively abundant in terms of both density and species diversity in comparison with other biomes but are threatened by land-use changes and deforestation (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0050" refid="bib53 bib54 bib29 bib31 bib21">Okuda and Ashton, 2003; Okuda et al., 2003; Hu et al., 2008; Jing and Zhiyuan, 2011; Gavier-Pizarro et al., 2012</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">The objectives of this study were to map white-handed gibbons’ calling locations and to analyze how these locations are related to topographic features and three forest vertical components (FVCs)—a digital surface model (DSM), a digital terrain model (DTM), and canopy height (CH)—and convexity index (CI) as a topographic configuration (see abbreviation list at <ce:cross-ref id="cr0210" refid="sec0055">Appendix 1</ce:cross-ref>). All these components can be derived through a LiDAR census, which enables the spatiotemporal mapping of biomass and forest structure more efficiently than that developed by a conventional ground survey (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0215" refid="bib57">Okuda et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0220" refid="bib16">D’Oliveira et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). The rapid construction of FVCs by using this kind of remote sensing tool would allow the habitat condition of arboreal animals to be identified on an on-demand basis.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">We also used previously reported acoustic triangulation positioning methods in the field (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0225" refid="bib6">Brockelman and Ali, 1987</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0230" refid="bib10">Buckley et al., 2006</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0235" refid="bib24">Gilhooly et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>) by employing directional microphones from canopy towers to identify and locate white-handed gibbons’ calls in a lowland dipterocarp forest in Peninsular Malaysia. We tested the hypothesis that white-handed gibbons would prefer higher FVCs as their calling locations because higher FVCs allow for greater sound propagation. If this is the case, we predict that the FVCs of their calling locations will be higher than those over the whole area. Such information could be used for mapping the optimal areas for calling locations, which could in turn be used for forest management to conserve arboreal animals on the basis of their forest canopy preferences.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0025">Study area</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">The study was conducted in a lowland dipterocarp forest within the Pasoh Forest Reserve (2°59′N, 102°18′E; 89–143 m a.s.l.) in the state of Negeri Sembilan, about 70 km southeast of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0005"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0240" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). An area of about 2400 ha has been maintained as research forest since the late 1970 s (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0245" refid="bib4">Ashton et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>). The mean annual rainfall from 1996 to 2015 measured at a research station within the reserve was 1801 mm, with distinct peaks in mean monthly precipitation in March–May (166 mm) and October–December (213 mm) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0250" refid="bib58">Okuda et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The topography consists mainly of flat alluvial areas, with smaller expanses of swales, riverine areas, and gently rolling hills (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0055" refid="bib43 bib55">Manokaran et al., 2004; Okuda et al., 2004a</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">In the past, we have heard the gibbons’ calls frequently in the primary forest but much less often in the regenerating forest adjacent to the oil palm plantation (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0255" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b). The white-handed gibbons forage mainly within the canopy layers, but they sometime utilize understory tree species when inhabiting a logged regenerating forest located 5–6 km southwest of the study site (part of Serting Forest Reserve; K. Muangkhum, Thailand Institute of Scientific and Technological Research, personal communication 2003, at Pasoh). By definition, most such understory tree species are &lt; 15 m in height (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0260" refid="bib42">Manokaran and Lafrankie, 1990</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">The overall vegetation type in the reserve is lowland dipterocarp forest, which is characterized by a high proportion of species in the Dipterocarpaceae family (e.g., <ce:italic>Shorea leprosula, S. acuminata, S. maxwelliana, Dipterocapus crinitis, D. cornutus</ce:italic>) (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0060" refid="bib68 bib80 bib81">Symington, 1943; Wyatt-Smith, 1961, 1964</ce:cross-refs>). On the basis of floristic evidence, the primary forest at the study site has not undergone major disturbance and appears to be representative of the lowland forest of the south-central Malay Peninsula (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0065" refid="bib36 bib42">Kochummen et al., 1990; Manokaran and Lafrankie, 1990</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">Southern and eastern alleys (shown in white in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0265" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b) present in the reserve were selectively logged in the mid to late 1950s under the Malayan Uniform System (MUS). At the time of this study, these alley patches were still naturally regenerating (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0270" refid="bib57">Okuda et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>) and are hereafter referred to as “regenerating forest.” Under the MUS, only commercially valuable timber (with a lower cutting limit of 45 cm in diameter at breast height) was supposed to be extracted. Unmerchantable trees were eliminated by poison girdling to build a floristically homogeneous forest while encouraging the regeneration of merchantable (timber) tree species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0070" refid="bib73 bib41">Thang, 1987; Manokaran, 1998</ce:cross-refs>). The regenerating forest is still in a state of high competition among the canopy-forming species, which have a smaller crown size than trees in the primary forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0275" refid="bib54">Okuda et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>). This has resulted in a homogeneous canopy surface structure, with the absence of distinct emergent trees that penetrate the canopy layers, as commonly seen in unlogged primary forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0280" refid="bib56">Okuda et al., 2004b</ce:cross-ref>). Such a homogeneous canopy height is likely a result of a prolonged self-thinning processes among the prospective canopy and emergent components (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0285" refid="bib56">Okuda et al., 2004b</ce:cross-ref>) or the absence of artificial thinning that was supposed to be undertaken under the MUS but that never occurred as logging shifted from lowland forest to hill dipterocarp forest (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0075" refid="bib73 bib41">Thang, 1987; Manokaran, 1998</ce:cross-refs>). The regenerating forest exhibits a high density of medium-sized trees (&lt; 40 cm in diameter) with very limited numbers of large trees (&gt; 50 cm), which also contributes to the forest’s homogenous physiognomy (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0080" refid="bib57 bib58">Okuda et al., 2019, 2021</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Within the Pasoh Forest Reserve, our 520-ha study site consists of primary forest (39% of the total study site) with no indications of previous logging, regenerating forest as defined above (52%), and oil palm plantation (9%) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0290" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0015" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0030">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0035">Forest vertical components</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">We estimated the FVCs (DSM, DTM, and CH) from airborne LiDAR data acquired in March 2011 across the entire study site (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0295" refid="bib57">Okuda et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). DSM was derived as canopy surface height from the first LiDAR pulse, and DTM represented ground surface elevation and was developed from the last reflecting pulse. The CH was calculated as the difference between the two. Across the 520-ha (2 km × 2.6 km) study site, DTM, DSM, and CH were resampled in every 2.5-m × 2.5-m grid interval. In total, 833,841 grid points were collected.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Although the LiDAR data were acquired 8 years before our survey of white-handed gibbons’ calls, two LiDAR surveys conducted across the study site in 2003 and 2011 showed that the vertical variation (increase) of average CH was 0.2 m y<ce:sup loc="post">–1</ce:sup> in primary forest and 0.28 m y<ce:sup loc="post">–1</ce:sup> in the regenerating forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0300" refid="bib57">Okuda et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>), suggesting that the difference in CH between the present study in 2019 and the last LiDAR census in 2013 will be within these ranges, at most. We assumed that DTM values have not changed, since no erosion or landslides have been observed.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0040">Calling point detection by acoustic triangulation positioning</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Calling orientation (direction bearing toward the calls) was measured from the top of two canopy towers, one made of aluminum alloy located in the southern alley of the primary forest (Tower 1, built in 1992; 54 m in height) and the other made of wood located 400 m north of the aluminum alloy tower (Tower 2, built in 2003; 45 m) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0305" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">White-handed gibbon calls, comprising female great calls and male responses, were identified and confirmed as white-handed gibbon calling on the basis of their species-specific vocalizations (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0085" refid="bib61 bib12 bib70 bib71 bib72">Reichard, 1998; Cheyne, 2007; Terleph et al., 2015, 2018a, 2018b</ce:cross-refs>). We marked and recorded the bearing angle from both towers as one calling point as long as the calling activities lasted.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">The two towers sit on a high ridgetop, and there are no physical or visual obstacles around them that interrupt sound transmission. The acoustic data of white-handed gibbons were obtained from 8 to 15 December 2018, 28 February to 4 March 2019, and 28 July to 4 August 2019. The daily observation period extended from 06:30 to 12:00 h.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">In total, 49 calling points were identified. From the bearing angles of a call observed simultaneously from both towers, we triangulated to the calling point (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0010"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0310" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). The bearing angles were determined by both directional (shotgun) microphones (SGH-6, Zoom Corp., Tokyo, Japan) and hand-held compasses. When the volume input at the acoustic receiver (Handy Recorder H6, Zoom Corp.) connected to the directional microphones was maximum on the sound level meter, the angles oriented from the white-handed gibbon’s call were simultaneously confirmed aurally by researchers at the top of the two towers.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Although the shotgun microphone has a range of ± 10–15° (5–7.5° on both sides) of the maximum volumes, we found that this combined detection system (microphone + human hearing) enabled the detection of orientation within an angle range of &lt; 5°. The range of detection accuracy was confirmed experimentally by generating mechanical and human calls from 150 to 250 m away from a detection point on the roof of a building (32 m height) of Hiroshima University (Higashi-Hiroshima, Japan); such preliminary trials were also performed at the study site in Pasoh when we heard the white-handed gibbons’ calls near the tower (in the same distance range). We also visually confirmed this range by observing calling white-handed gibbons with binoculars or the naked eye when possible, that is, when calling white-handed gibbons were identified (mostly within &lt;150 m) from the tower; we did this only to verify our ability to identify the orientation range of the directional microphones.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">We sometimes observed white-handed gibbon groups staying, moving around, and foraging in the canopy without calling. In such cases, we did not identify their locations. However, if the activities were accompanied or led by calling, we recorded the calling points. In the identification of the 49 calling points, we detected the gibbons’ calling first by ear, then confirmed the direction of the call with the shotgun microphones, and read the bearings (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0315" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">For each calling point detected, we extended circular areas to four radius sizes of 20, 50, 100, and 150 m to delineate the calling location in which the DSM, DTM, and CH were sampled from LiDAR data spatially mapped in every 2.5-m × 2.5-m grid interval (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0320" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). The use of four calling location sizes allowed us to consider the probability of detecting their calls; that is, the detection probability decreases as a function of distance from the calling point but can be secured by using a larger sampling circle (i.e., 150 m), as long as statistical analyses prove the difference in FVCs between calling locations and the whole study site (see <ce:cross-ref id="cr0325" refid="sec0030">Section 3.3</ce:cross-ref>). This was done based on simple geometric calculations for triangulating a point from the tower; for example, for a triangle with a 5° ( ± 2.5° on both sides of the bearing angle at which we detected the calling point) vertex at the tower and a circle of 150-m radius, a distance of 3400 m covers all the FVC data. Therefore, given that the bearing angle range is 10° at the tower, a circle of 150-m radius can cover all prospective FVCs at a distance up to 1700 m. Although white-handed gibbon calls can be detected up to 2 km (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0330" refid="bib20">Francis, 2001</ce:cross-ref>), we excluded calling points detected at distances &gt; 1200 m from either of the towers, because in previous ground surveys of yellow-cheeked crested gibbon (<ce:italic>Nomascus gabriellae</ce:italic>) the authors reported that human surveyors’ detection capability ranged from 1.5 to 2.0 km depending upon the topography (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0090" refid="bib74 bib76">Vu and Dong, 2015; Vu et al., 2016</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0045">Statistical analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">FVCs were mapped in Global Mapper v. 12 software (Blue Marble Geographics, Hallowell, ME, USA). The DSM, DTM, and CH values were sampled from the four circular calling locations with radii of 20, 50, 100, and 150 m. FVCs were collected at 2.5-m intervals within each calling location, resulting in 201 grid points derived from LiDAR data (DSM, DTM, and CH) at a radius of 20 m, 1257 at 50 m, 5013 at 100 m, and 11,251 at 150 m. By pooling the 49 calling points, we used 9870, 61,580, and 245,627, and 551,274 grid points, respectively.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">From all FVCs pooled for all 49 calling points, we randomly selected 3000 grid samples for each calling location size and compared them with the same number of samples collected from the whole study site (727,899 samples), excluding the oil palm plantation, using a randomization function (Microsoft Excel 2019) on <ce:italic>x-</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>y-</ce:italic>coordinates within the study site. The random sampling was performed five times for each calling location size for all FVCs because we were concerned that the large difference in sample size between the calling locations and the whole study site might reduce the power of probability estimation, as is the case with a <ce:italic>t-</ce:italic>test (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0335" refid="bib32">Jnobuyuki, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Using this method, we examined whether the frequency distribution patterns differed between the original and average values of randomly sampled populations, and we found no significant differences (χ<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> test, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &gt; 0.5) between the two populations for all FVCs.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">For these comparisons, we used Welch’s <ce:italic>t</ce:italic>-test in the Bell Curve add-in package (SSRI, Tokyo, Japan) in Excel 2013 v. 15.0.5015 software (Microsoft Inc., Redmond, WA, USA). Because some of the randomly sampled FVCs in calling locations and the whole study site exhibited heterogeneous variance (according to Levene’s test), we used Welch’s <ce:italic>t</ce:italic>-test, which is suitable for testing the differences in mean values between samples with heterogeneous variance (i.e., heteroscedasticity; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0340" refid="bib14">Data Novia, 2002</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">The relationship between CH and DTM for the whole study site was analyzed under the assumption that ridgetops or upper hillslopes tend to be vegetated by taller trees. Our empirical observations and tree census data measured in primary and regenerating forest areas of the Pasoh Forest Reserve indicated that larger or taller trees are more abundant in the upper hill area than in the lower swampy area, with a significant difference in average CH (40 m in upper hills area vs. 27 m in the lower swampy area, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.01; <ce:cross-refs id="crs0095" refid="bib55 bib57">Okuda et al., 2004a, 2019</ce:cross-refs>). In addition, we predicted that sound can propagate more effectively from ridgetops or upper hillslopes than from valley bottoms, where sound waves can be intercepted by the surrounding vegetated hills, as dense vegetation attenuates sound propagation (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0345" refid="bib11">Bullen and Fricke, 1982</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0350" refid="bib19">Fang and Ling, 2003</ce:cross-ref>). If this is the case, convex areas should be more frequently used as calling points than convex areas. Therefore, we employed a convexity index (CI) to analyze how calling locations are related to topographic features. For this analysis, we divided the study site into 20-m × 20-m sub-blocks and calculated CI for each; CI &gt; 0 in convex areas (e.g., ridgetop or mid-slope), CI &lt; 0 in concave areas (e.g., valley), and CI = 0 in flat areas, relative to the eight surrounding sub-blocks.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">We calculated the CI from the average of four corners of DTM (DTM_a) and of 12 points of DTM surrounding the sub-block (DTM_b), as follows:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="eqn0005">
                              <ce:chem>CI (%) = (DTM_a – DTM_b) / (DTM_a) × 100</ce:chem>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>
                     </ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">In the same manner, we calculated CI in larger sub-blocks (50 m × 50 m and 100 m × 100 m). We did not enlarge sub-blocks beyond 100 m × 100 m, primarily because a sub-block is represented by only one set of FVC values, regardless of the spatial positioning of <ce:italic>x</ce:italic>- and <ce:italic>y</ce:italic>-coordinates of the FVC detected within the sub-block. Second, the study site sometimes included different types of topographic features (e.g., ridge top, valley, lowland swampy area) within a sub-block of larger size (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0355" refid="bib58">Okuda et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The CI is a revised version of the index proposed by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0360" refid="bib82">Yamakura et al. (1995)</ce:cross-ref>, which was defined as only the difference in DTM between the focal and surrounding sub-blocks. We normalized the index (%). Finally, we used Welch’s <ce:italic>t</ce:italic>-test to compare the CI of sub-blocks containing the 49 calling points and that of 500 sub-blocks randomly chosen from the whole study site. Because there were fewer than 500 sub-blocks of 100 m × 100 m over the whole study site, we did not employ random sampling in this case.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Spatial variation of elevation at the study site originates mostly from the many small hills and valleys, not from the difference between the large hills in the eastern part of the Pasoh Forest Reserve (peak elevation &gt; 600 m a.s.l.) and the lower flat area.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">To evaluate the potential calling locations and to develop a map of potentially suitable calling locations, besides the area we identified as such, we normalized the FVC values by ranking them into eight scores (–2 to +5) in each sub-block. This was done only for the sub-block size of 20 m × 20 m in order to visualize it at higher resolution. The ranking was obtained by calculating how far the FVC (e.g., DTM) of a sub-block varies from the mean value of the FVC at calling points; for example, if the difference between the DTM value of a sub-block (DTM<ce:inf loc="post">SD</ce:inf>) and mean FVC value of calling points is ≥ 2.0 × SD (standard deviation) of the mean FVC value of calling points, we ranked the sub-block with a score of 5. The highest score was 5, given that any sub-block further from the mean FVC value to the right in a distribution curve has a higher probability to be a potential calling point. Similarly, the scores were given for every 0.5 × SD class until the range was less than –1.0 × SD (lower than 1 SD from the mean FVC value of the calling points; see <ce:cross-ref id="cr0365" refid="sec0060">Appendix 2</ce:cross-ref>). Because we aimed to extract the area with a <ce:italic>higher</ce:italic> probability of calling locations, we did not extend to classes below –1.0 × SD. Hereafter, the rank given to each sub-block is referred to as the “FVC score,” which was used for principal component analysis (PCA; R v. 4.0.2) in order to bundle elements of FVCs to some components and to visualize how the probable area of potential calling locations varies among land-use types. This analysis allows spatial projection of the gap from the area extrapolated to be potential calling locations to the present land-use types.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0035" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0050">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">Using acoustic triangulation from the towers, we detected 12 calling points in December 2018, 10 in February and March 2019, and 27 in July and August 2019, for a total of 49 calling points (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0370" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">The calling points were spatially concentrated in the primary forest, where they occurred at much higher density (0.21 ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>) than in the regenerating forest (0.03 ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0375" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b). This difference in density may have been affected by the location of the towers, as both are placed in the primary forest and most of the calling points in the regenerating forest were detected at distances &gt; 700 m from either of the two towers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0380" refid="sec0065">Appendix 3</ce:cross-ref>). However, it is notable that calling was rarely detected from the southern alley, close to Tower 1. When we focused on the area around Tower 1 (~90 ha in total, 47% primary, 53% regenerating), calling density was 0.33 ha<ce:sup loc="post">–1</ce:sup> in the primary forest and 0.04 ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> in the regenerating forest.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">The average DTM of randomly selected calling grid points for all calling location sizes (from 20- to 150-m radius) was significantly higher (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001) than that of points in the whole study site, as shown in the frequency distribution pattern of DTM (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0015"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0385" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>a; see also <ce:cross-ref id="cr0390" refid="sec0070">Appendix 4</ce:cross-ref>). The same trend was seen in the mean DSM (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0395" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>b, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0400" refid="sec0070">Appendix 4</ce:cross-ref>). These findings were consistent across all five trials of statistical tests on randomly selected samples from the calling locations and the whole study site.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">CH was significantly different between calling locations and the whole study site for all calling location sizes in the five trials of random sampling (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001, Appendix 4). The difference in mean DTM was 5.3 m between calling locations and the whole study site (20-m calling locations, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0405" refid="sec0070">Appendix 4</ce:cross-ref>), which is only 4.8% of its average value in the whole study site. In contrast, the difference in mean CH was 2.8 m (20-m calling locations), representing 13.3% of its average value in the whole study site.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">To consider the spatial variation of the three parameters across the study site, we examined the coefficient of variation, which was much higher for CH (0.455) than for DSM (0.112) and DTM (0.078). This greater variation of CH is due primarily to the fact that CH reflects tree crown height, which includes the height of the tree apex and peripheral branches, as well as neighboring trees and their foliage gaps. These findings indicate that white-handed gibbons show a stronger preference for calling at sites with higher CH, when possible. On the basis of all the above results, it is most likely that calling locations are selected in higher canopy trees (as shown by the higher CH) located at higher DTM sites (the base of the forest floor). Consequently, higher DSM sites appear to be chosen for calling.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">In relation to topography, CI of the calling points was significantly higher (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.01) than that obtained in the sub-blocks (20 m × 20 m) over the whole study site (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0020"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0410" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0415" refid="sec0070">Appendix 4</ce:cross-ref>), indicating that topographically convex areas tend to be chosen as calling locations rather than concave areas (lower slopes or valleys). Similarly, when the sub-block was enlarged to 50 m × 50 m and 100 m × 100 m, the CI differences between calling points and sub-blocks were significant (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.05) for both sub-block sizes.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">In the PCA of the FVC scores, PC-1 and PC-2 reflect 90% of total variance of the FVC scores (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0005"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0420" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). PC-1 had large loadings for DTM (0.60) and DSM (0.71), whereas for PC-2 CH accounted for most of the loading (0.85). These findings indicate that PC-1 reflects the surface height configuration and PC-2 covers the variation of CH. Although the CI showed a large loading on component 3 (–0.96), we used only PC-1 and PC-2 for spatial mapping of potential calling locations (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0025"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0425" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>), because PC-3 made only a small contribution (0.09) to total variance (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0430" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>) (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0010"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0435" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">The PC-1 and PC-2 scores were significantly different among the three land-use types. The PC-1 scores were significantly higher (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001, Scheffé’s test) in the regenerating forest than in the primary forest and oil palm plantation, whereas the PC-2scores were significantly higher (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001, Scheffé’s test) in the primary forest than in the other two land-use types (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0015"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0440" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>). These findings indicate that a great number of potentially suitable calling locations exist in the regenerating forest, but this is offset by the lower CH there. We identified no such suitable places in the oil palm plantation on the basis of the variation of PC-1 and PC-2 scores (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0445" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0040" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0055">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">Our results indicate that areas of taller CH and higher DSM were preferentially chosen as the white-handed gibbons’ calling locations, which can be partly attributed to forest floor elevation determined by DTM (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0450" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0455" refid="sec0070">Appendix 4</ce:cross-ref>). Although the study site consists of a flat alluvial area with an elevation range of 89–143 m, its topography shows complex spatial variation at the small scale (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0460" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b). Ridgetops and the upper parts of hills tended to be chosen as calling locations rather than the valley or lower slope areas, as indicated by the significant difference in CI between the calling points and the whole study site (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0465" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, white-handed gibbons seem to choose points with higher CH on ridgetops and upper hillslopes as calling locations.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">Sound waves are intercepted by physical obstacles such as dense vegetation (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0470" refid="bib19">Fang and Ling, 2003</ce:cross-ref>) and convex topography. Therefore, for their intergroup communication, it is beneficial for white-handed gibbons to call from areas with higher FVC (although this is not the case for intragroup communications). If white-handed gibbons were to call at lower positions in trees or in valleys, the sound might be intercepted by dense vegetation and hills or ridges or be non-directionally diffused. White-handed gibbons are highly territorial animals (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0475" refid="bib2">Asensio et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>), and their calling is one of the most significant behaviors used to maintain their territorial ranges (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0100" refid="bib49 bib12 bib46 bib28">Mitani, 1988; Cheyne, 2007; Marshall et al., 2009; Ham et al., 2016</ce:cross-refs>). The preference for higher FVCs was also reported in the Kloss gibbon (<ce:italic>Hylobates klossii</ce:italic>), which favors hillside forest with the tallest trees as calling locations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0480" refid="bib79">Whitmore, 1984</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, greater CH is one of the most distinct and advantageous features for white-handed gibbon calling locations (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0105" refid="bib79 bib51 bib26">Whitmore, 1984; O’Brien et al., 2004; Gray et al., 2010</ce:cross-refs>), although this may not be the case in areas with greater topographic complexity than at our study site (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0485" refid="bib77">Vu et al., 2018a</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">Calling points were more frequent in the primary forest than in the regenerating forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0490" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b; no calls were recorded in the oil palm plantation). We are uncertain whether the lower density of calling points in the regenerating forest is due to fewer white-handed gibbons being there or lower calling rates in disturbed forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0495" refid="bib33">Johns, 1986</ce:cross-ref>). Alternatively, the group of white-handed gibbons calling from regenerating forest might have been pushed into the area by the territorial behavior of other groups in the primary forest. Also, the difference in density of calling points may be affected by the location of the towers, as both are placed in the primary forest. Nevertheless, we heard white-handed gibbons calling a few times immediately after logging operations elsewhere (conducted in 2003–2004) in the southeastern end of the Pasoh Forest Reserve, but heard no calling there afterward. Moreover, whenever we surveyed on the ground for tree mapping or other objectives (not for white-handed gibbon recordings) within the regenerating forest zone (logged in the 1950s; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0500" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b), we seldom observed white-handed gibbons’ activities (including calling) there. It is notable that only a few calls and lower calling density were detected in the regenerating forest (0.03 vs. 0.4 ha<ce:sup loc="post">–1</ce:sup> in the primary forest) close to the canopy tower at the southern end of the primary forest (Tower 1, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0505" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b), suggesting that proximity to the tower may not be the underlying issue (i.e., the lack of observed calling is not primarily due to the longer distance from the observation points). It also should be noted that calling density does not directly represent the number of groups or individuals, as the calling locations were sampled repeatedly for three seasons within the study site. Nevertheless, we presume that there are at least five groups around the towers (i.e., within a 1.0-km radius of either of the towers) within the primary forest, considering their steady calling locations. However, more frequent observation and calling point detection may be required for monitoring and identifying each of the groups.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">As summary, on the basis of our observations, fewer calls in the regenerating forest might be attributed to (1) low group density in the area; (2) less of a need for territorial defense calls due to larger, less desirable home ranges, which would result in most of their calls being for other reasons, such as pair bonding (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0510" refid="bib23">Geissmann, 2002</ce:cross-ref>); (3) the presence of hunters in the area; or (4) a combination of all of the above. Another issue to consider is that during the time since logging and our LiDAR census, some trees may have reached an acceptable height for white-handed gibbons to use as calling points - this is why we could detect the some calling points in the regenerating forest even though the number is still lower than that in the primary forest. Food availability may also help to explain the difference in white-handed gibbons’ calling density between the regenerating and primary forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0515" refid="bib18">Fan et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>), but we do not have enough data to examine this. Therefore, our results call for a more precise analysis and further monitoring in relation to the calling pattern and FVCs.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">In addition, wild boar are frequently hunted within the oil palm plantation and near the boundary area with the regenerating forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0520" refid="bib30">Ickes and Thomas, 2003</ce:cross-ref>), and shooting sounds have quelled white-handed gibbons’ activities and driven them from this area of the regenerating forest to the inner part of the forest reserve (primary forest; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0525" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>b). During our observations, we found that one group often observed near Tower 2 stopped calling after repeated hunting sounds and barking of hound dogs nearby. We could not find them there for more than 3 months. <ce:cross-ref id="cr0530" refid="bib79">Whitmore (1984)</ce:cross-ref> reported that white-handed gibbons almost entirely stopped calling after logging.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">PCA based on the FVC scores revealed a large number of potentially suitable calling locations even in the regenerating forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0535" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, upper graph) in terms of DTM and DSM, both of which are a reflection of elevation, although the observed frequency of white-handed gibbons’ calling was lower in the regenerating forest. In contrast, the map of suitable calling locations based on PC-2 (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0540" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, bottom graph), with a high CH loading, was different from the map based on PC-1. The highest ranking class of PC-2 (≥ 3) is more frequent in the primary forest than in the regenerating forest (2.7% of total number of sub-blocks vs. 0.9%). Considering the mobility of white-handed gibbons within their territory and the rigidity of stems and branches where they stay and start calling, it appears that they may need large trees and complex canopies for their habitat.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">These findings suggest that several parameters should be incorporated in the spatial analysis of suitable white-handed gibbons’ calling locations, not only topographic parameters but also CH, which is related to canopy surface structure. Nevertheless, PCA based on multiple variables is effective for extracting the gap area where more attention is needed for preserving white-handed gibbons’ calling sites, and such spatial mapping may contribute to protection of their habitat.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0045" view="all">
                  <ce:label>6</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0060">Further development of detection tools</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">Our mapping method for detecting calling locations could be improved by increasing the number of spotting sites (e.g., canopy towers) and using a longer observation period and automatic recording devices (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0545" refid="bib75">Vu and Tran, 2019</ce:cross-ref>) with bearing information on calling orientations. If rigid canopy towers are not available, quickly constructed towers placed on higher ridgetops or temporary platforms made near the top of the canopy or emergent trees would suffice. Digital mapping of DSM and DTM can now be achieved by using inexpensive drone LiDAR devices. Recently, drone LiDAR has been proved to be a cost-effective tool in mapping DTM, DSM, and CH in dense tropical forest (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0550" refid="bib16">D’Oliveira et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>); the authors claimed that the drone’s low-altitude flight and speed favored the production of greater point cloud density relative to airborne LiDAR. If such devices are not available, the use of conventional aerial photography and stereoscopes will work for developing a three-dimensional canopy surface model. If ground elevations are available or can be measured by ground survey, this conventional technique will ensure that DTM and CH will be accurately spatially mapped on the focal area. Such measures would enable mapping of potential white-handed gibbons’ calling locations, allowing for rapid assessment. These higher resolution canopy mapping can allow researchers to measure “on-demand FVC” and thus provide the most updated information on the habitat of arboreal wildlife species, such as canopy height structure and density, spatial heterogeneity, and tree species components that can serve as a surrogate index for their habitat selection, as shown in other gibbon species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0555" refid="bib50">Muzaffar et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0560" refid="bib64">Sarma et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) and another primate (orangutan)(<ce:cross-ref id="cr0565" refid="bib15">Davies et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0050" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0065">Funding</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">The present study was financially supported by the <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Japan Society for the Promotion of Sciences</ce:grant-sponsor> (grant no. <ce:grant-number refid="gs1">18K06418</ce:grant-number>, from 2018 to 2022, grant no. <ce:grant-number refid="gs2">19KK0269</ce:grant-number> from 2019-2022), NEF Commemorative Grant Fund (<ce:grant-sponsor id="gs2" sponsor-id="http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/501100011904" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Nagao Natural Environment Foundation</ce:grant-sponsor>, Tokyo, Jpana) and Kobelco fund (Kobelco Ltd., Tokyo, Japan).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0070">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0075">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">We thank Mr. Ahmad Awang and Zamri Ahmad of the Forest Research Institute Malaysia, Kuala Lumpur, for their assistance with the field surveys and collection of tree census data at the Pasoh Forest Reserve. The present study was a part of a joint research project between the Forest Research Institute of Malaysia, Universiti Teknologi Malaysia, Universiti Putra Malaysia, and Hiroshima University.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
